  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>

        <div rend="parallel">
          <p xml:id="AN159-kilavi">piriviṭai vēṟupaṭṭa talaimakaḷait tōḻi <app><lem>vaṟpuṟuttiyatu</lem><rdg wit="#C7">vaṟpuṟīiyatu</rdg></app>.</p>
          <p xml:lang="en">How the confidante consoled HER who had undergone changes in the time of separation.</p>
        </div>
        <div rend="parallel">
            <lg xml:id="AN159">
              <l><anchor n="1"/>teṇkaḻi viḷainta veṇka lu<supplied>p</supplied>piṉ</l>
              <l>koḷḷai cāṟṟiya koṭunuka voḻukai</l>
              <l>yuraṉuṭaic cuvala pakaṭu parappi</l>
              <l>yumaṇuyirt tiṟanta voḻikka laṭuppiṉ</l>
              <l>vaṭiyuṟu pakaḻik koṭuvi lāṭava</l>
              <l>raṇaṅkuṭai nōṉcilai vaṇaṅka vāṅkip</l>
              <l>pallā ṉeṭunirai taḻīik kalleṉa</l>
              <l>varumu<supplied>ṉai</supplied> yalaitta perumpuka<supplied>l</supplied> valattar</l>
              <l>kaṉaikuraṟ kaṭuntuṭip pāṇi tūṅki</l>
              <l>yuvalaik kaṇ<supplied>ṇi</supplied>ya rūṉpuḻuk kayaruṅ</l>
              <l>kavalai kātala riṟantaṉa reṉanaṉi</l>
              <l>yavalaṅkoḷ ḷēṉmaṟ kātalan tōḻi</l>
              <l>vicumpi ṉallēṟu cilaikkuñ cēṭcimai</l>
              <l>naṟumpūñ cāraṟ kuṟumpoṟaik kuṇātu</l>
              <l>vilkeḻu taṭakkai velpōr vāṉavaṉ</l>
              <l>miñiṟumūcu kavuḷa ciṟukaṇ yāṉait</l>
              <l>toṭiyuṭait taṭamarup poṭiya nūṟik</l>
              <l>koṭumuṭi kākkuṅ kurūukka ṇeṭumatiṟ</l>
              <l>cēṇviḷaṅku ciṟappi ṉāmū reytiṉu</l>
              <l>māṇṭamain tuṟaiyuna <supplied>ra</supplied>llarniṉ</l>
              <l>pūṇṭāṅ kākam poruntutaṉ maṟantē.</l>
            </lg>
            <lg xml:lang="en">
                <l>Saying “[our] lover has gone to traverse crossroads, (11)</l>
                <l>where men with curved bows [and] refined arrows, (5)</l>
                <l>being very joyful winners who had noisily harassed the difficult frontier (8)</l>
                <l>by tightly bending [their] awsome sturdy bows, (6)</l>
                <l>[and] surrounding a large herd of many cows, (7a-c)</l>
                <l>[now] sway in the rhythm of the fierce Tuṭi drum with a bellowing voice, (9)</l>
                <l>[wearing] leaf chaplets, [and] prepare meat [and] rice (10)</l>
                <l>on the remaining stone ovens that were left, sighing, by saltmerchants, (4)</l>
                <l>when releasing the bulls with strong necks (3)</l>
                <l>from the carts with curved yokes, who had proclaimed the price (2)</l>
                <l>of the salt in white stones that had ripened in the clear backwaters, (1)</l>
                <l>I don’t feel much affliction, beloved friend. (11d-12)</l>
                <l>Even if he were to obtain Āmūr, the excellence of [its] tall fortifications</l>
                <l>[manned] with brilliant eyes shining into the distance, that is guarded by Koṭumuṭi, (18f.)</l>
                <l>destroying, so that [their] ring-possessing broad tusks snap, (17)</l>
                <l>the small-eyed elephants, [their] temples swarming with bees, (16)</l>
                <l>of the Vāṉavaṉ of victorious battle, [his] broad hands holding a bow, (15)</l>
                <l>ast of the short hillocks with slopes of fragrant flowers (14)</l>
                <l>[and] distant peaks where good thunder reverberates in the sky, (13)</l>
                <l>he is not one to stay content there, (20)</l>
                <l>forgetting how he fits with your ornament-bearing chest. (21)</l>
            </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
  </text>

